TY  - JOUR
AU  - Choi, Jaewon
AU  - Richardson, Matthew
AU  - Whitelaw, Robert F
T1  - Capital Structure Priority Effects in Durations, Stock-Bond Comovements, and Factor Pricing Models
PY  - 2022
Y1  - 2022/09/01
DO  - 10.1093/rapstu/raac003
JO  - The Review of Asset Pricing Studies
JA  - Rev Asset Pric Stud
VL  - 12
IS  - 3
SP  - 706
EP  - 753
SN  - 2045-9920
AB  - We show theoretically and empirically that the durations of corporate securities are monotonically related to their capital structure priority, with equity often having a negative duration. The magnitude of this effect increases with firm leverage. We use these insights to challenge existing results on stock-bond comovements and factor pricing. For example, though overlooked, higher leverage and lower priority reduce the correlation between corporate security and government bond returns, and these variables explain time-series and cross-sectional variation in correlations; traditional market model regressions significantly understate corporate bond betas; and regressions on standard term and default factors dramatically overstate interest rate and default risk. (JEL G12, G13)
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rapstu/raac003
ER  - 



